An '''Idée reçue''' ([[Wikipedia:Manual of Style (pronunciation)/IPA vs. other pronunciation symbols|WBO]]: ''«ee DAY ruh soo»'') is a received, or accepted, idea.  This term was used by [[Gustave Flaubert]] in his work [[Dictionary of Received Ideas|''Le Dictionnaire des idées reçues'']] to refer to a catchphrases and platitudes, most of which are as paradoxical as they are insipid.